observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the:

LCE, thru the Municipal Accountant:
serve written notices to all concerned accountable officers requiring settlement of their outstanding cash advances and institute legal action against them, if warranted;
ensure that no additional cash advance is granted to the Municipal Treasurer unless the purpose of grant is for official travel;
consider imposing the “No liquidation, no cash advance” policy to enforce settlement of long outstanding cash advances; and
in all instances, ensure that each provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 are strictly observed and that all cash advances are fully liquidated at the end of the year; and

Municipal Accountant:
immediately submit the Audit Team’s requested documents relevant to the unliquidated cash advances for filing of appropriate cases against erring AOs;
enforce strict monitoring of grant and liquidation of cash advances to ensure that no additional cash advance is granted unless the previous one has been duly liquidated and accounted for.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all supplies and materials and prepare the report thereon, reconcile the results of the count with available records in the Accounting and General Services Offices and submit the inventory report to the Audit Team;

MDRRMO, MSWDO and GSO to (i) immediately submit the required distribution lists and proof of receipts for the relief goods given to various beneficiaries as well as the inventory of undistributed goods; and (ii) render satisfactory explanation on the delayed reporting of the result of distribution in connection with the COVID-19 operations of the LGU; 

Punong Barangays concerned to submit the required distribution lists of the relief goods assigned to their barangays to facilitate the preparation of the report of the MDRRMO, MSWDO and the GSO; 

Municipal GSO (i) ensure that issuances of supplies and materials are supported with duly signed RIS to establish accountability on the part of the end-users, particularly those departments assigned for the distribution of relief goods; and (ii) submit to the Municipal Accountant the monthly summary of supplies and materials issued duly supported by the RIS as basis for recording expenses; and

Municipal Accountant, upon submission of the required summary report and distribution list and the inventory report by the concerned offices, make the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balances of the Inventory accounts.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant i) thru the BAC, MDRRM Officer and other concerned offices, submit the lacking documents including the rice and medicines distribution list; and ii) thoroughly review the disbursements, as part of the internal audit service of the Municipality to determine completeness of supporting documents before certifying the DVs;

Municipal Mayor, thru the BAC and BAC Secretariat, i) strictly comply with the requirements of GPPB Circular No. 1-2020 and other relevant laws, rules and regulations on procurement; 
ii) submit the revised BGCM fund utilization report and refund the unutilized amount of ₱415,250.00 to the national treasury; and 
iii) cause the creation of LGU website to comply with the State’s policy on full disclosure of all transactions involving public interest;

BAC i) provide explanation/justification on the high price of 8,140 sacks of rice procured; and ii) ensure that the unit prices of goods being requested are within the ceiling set or are based on the prevailing rates provided by appropriate government offices; and

Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer thoroughly review the propriety of charges against appropriations/allotments and verify the balances of appropriations/allotments before affixing their signatures in the Obligation Requests and DVs.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer immediately reconcile their records on DRRMF in coordination with the MDRRM Officer; 

Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer cause the immediate transfer of the unexpended DRRMF to the LDRRMF STF bank account;


Municipal Accountant (i) record the DRRM funds received from other sources to the Trust Liabilities-DRRMF account; (ii) revise the report of the sources and utilization of the DRRMF in the NTFS to reflect the correct balances; and

MDRRM Officer (i) submit the supplemental LDRRMFIPs and AIPs for the abovementioned SBudgets and resolution and henceforth, ensure that PPAs funded by the LDRRMF are included in the LDRRMFIP and incorporated in the AIP; and (ii) submit to the Audit Team the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of the DRRMF duly certified correct by the Municipal Accountant in accordance with the prescribed deadline stated in Item 5.1.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-002.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Mayor (i) require the BAC and other concerned personnel involved in the emergency procurement to render explanation on the noted deficiencies; (ii) thru the BAC, strictly comply with the requirements of R.A. No. 9184, GPPB Circular No. 1-2020 and other relevant laws, rules and regulations on procurement; and (iii) thru the BAC and the General Services Officer, ensure that the Purchase Orders and Inspection and Acceptance Reports, contain detailed specification of items procured and delivered, respectively;

BAC i) provide explanation on the high price of procured commercial rice and medical supplies as well as on the procurement of room accommodations, transportation services and various supplies used for COVID-19 operations; ii) ensure that the unit prices of the items being requested are within the ceiling set or are based on the prevailing rates provided by appropriate government offices; iii) submit the certified copy of DOT Certificate of Authority to Operate of the two hotels/inns which were awarded with contracts for LSI and ROF room accommodations; iv) submit clear certified copies of the CY 2019 Annual ITR and Audited FS of CDYO Consumer Goods Trading duly stamped “received” by the BIR; v) ensure that the LGU negotiate only with legally, technically and financially capable supplier and exert all efforts to secure the most advantageous price for the LGU; and vi) thru the BAC Secretariat, strictly comply with the posting requirements of GPPB issuances;

MDRRM Officer submit the i) lists of quarantine facilities and the persons held including the duration of their stay in these facilities; and ii) list of DILG-endorsed names showing the arrival/flight details of the ROIs and LSIs; 

Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Accountant thoroughly review the propriety of charges against appropriations/allotments and verify the balances of appropriations/allotments before affixing their signatures in the Obligation Requests and DVs; and

Municipal Accountant i) thru the BAC, submit the lacking documents; and ii) thoroughly review the claims/DVs, as part of the Municipality’s internal audit system to ensure completeness and propriety of supporting documents before certifying the DVs.

We recommended that the:

LCE, through the Municipal Accountant, serve written notices to all concerned accountable officers (AOs) requiring settlement of their outstanding cash advances and institute legal action against them, if warranted;
Municipal Accountant:
review SLs, determine the cause/s of abnormal negative balance per AO and reconcile its individual balance with the balance of Advances to O&E per SUCA as at year-end and effect the necessary corrections, as appropriate;
prepare the schedule of all receivables, unliquidated CAs, and fund transfers pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 and COA Memorandum No. 2017-010 dated May 15, 2017 (RUCA-quarterly and SUCA-semestral);
reconstruct the SLs for the CAs of officers and employees totaling ₱2,490,645.37 as of December 31, 2019 and immediately submit the same to the Audit Team;
immediately submit the following documents relevant to the unliquidated cash advances for filing of appropriate cases against erring AOs:
Authenticated copy of Appointment of the AOs granted CA;
Designation or authority to draw CA;
Authenticated copy of AO’s fidelity bond;
Authenticated copy of demand letter of the LCE and proof of receipt by the AO and answer/explanation thereto, if any;
Paid check/s for the CA; and
Other relevant documents    
enforce strict monitoring of grant and liquidation of CAs to ensure that no additional CA is granted unless the previous one has been duly liquidated and accounted for; and
LCE and the Municipal Accountant, in all instances, ensure that each provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 are strictly observed and that all CAs are fully liquidated at the end of the year.

We recommended that the:

LCE, thru the MDRRM Officer, (i) authorize the drivers and other staff to claim only the reasonable amount of meal allowance in connection with transporting patients to Taytay and PPC since frequent travel is already part of their job; (ii) prevent the incurrence of unnecessary and excessive travel expenses by  scheduling the trips early in the morning so that they could return to their station within the day; and (iii) ensure completeness of details/information before approving the PRs and POs;
MDRRM Officer (i) provide basis for allowing more than one driver in each trip; and (ii) ensure that fuel charged to the MDRRM Fund are utilized only for activities related to disaster risk reduction and management;
Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) ensure that the van/bus rentals are procured in accordance with the procedures on procurement of goods and services as provided in R.A. No. 9184 and its IRR; and
Municipal Accountant thoroughly review the travel claims and enforce strict adherence to EO No. 77 and DILG MC No. 2019-82 in order to prevent the incurrence of irregular, excessive, unnecessary and extravagant expenditures.

We recommended that the:

LCE:
thru the Municipal Accountant, BAC and BAC Secretariat, (i) cause the immediate submission of the lacking documents; (ii) require the concerned officials to render satisfactory explanation for the deficiencies noted in audit; and (iii) henceforth, ensure strict compliance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2012-001 and COA Circular No. 2009-001 on complete documentation; 
demand submission of the draft and final report for the Urban Development Plan considering that the contract period had already ended, otherwise, impose liquidated damages against the Consulting Firm;
henceforth, secure authorization from the Sangguniang Bayan before entering into a contract with the winning bidder for transactions involving lump sum appropriations or  those presented in generic terms in the annual or supplemental budgets; and
thru the MPDC, evaluate the necessity of hiring consulting services to avoid incurrence of unnecessary expenditures;
BAC strictly abide by the standards set forth by RA No. 9184, its Revised I.R.R. and other relevant laws on the procurement of consulting services;
Municipal Accountant ensure the completeness of supporting documents before processing and certifying the DVs; and
LCE, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer (i) strictly adhere with the mandates of R.A. No. 7160, specifically on Sections 22(c) and 322 on authority limits and budgeting, respectively; and (ii) cause the reversion of unappropriated PS and MOOE to the current appropriations through an Appropriation Ordinance or Supplemental Budget to be enacted by Sangguniang Bayan.

We recommended that the:

LCE (i) reevaluate, through the Municipal Engineer (ME) and Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC), the number of infrastructure projects which were identified to be undertaken “by administration” and assess whether the Municipality’s limited manpower as well as its technical capability to undertake project is sufficient to allow project implementation and completion within the time schedule; and (ii) weigh the advantages and disadvantages of a “by administration” scheme and straight contracting and thereafter consider which is better without sacrificing the timely delivery of basic services and facilities needed by the public;
ME and the MPDC (i) reevaluate and complete the list of infrastructure projects in the monitoring report and provide all the minimum required information on the implementation of each project; and (ii) hasten the implementation of the infrastructure projects and make sure that all projects are strictly monitored and implemented in accordance with plans and schedules; 
Municipal Mayor, MPDC and the ME evaluate the programs and projects with remaining appropriations as of December 31, 2019, recommend to the Local Development Council the reprogramming of those which the LGU will no longer be able to implement due to causes not attributable to the fault or negligence of the municipal government and its officials, determine the unexpended balances of completed projects and recommend to the Local Finance Committee the re-appropriation of said balances to fund other priority programs and projects of the Municipality; and
LCE, ME and MPDC strictly comply with the guidelines of COA Circular No. 2013-004 regarding information and publicity of PPAs.

